@inproceedings{Minhass2023,
   abstract = {As Internet of Things (IoT) technologies proliferate and smart devices become more and more integrated into our daily lives and workplaces, it is becoming more and more important to address the complex issues of data security and privacy within smart homes and buildings. Even though the Internet of Things (IoT) has many benefits, such as remote control, real-time monitoring, and sophisticated security features, it also raises serious concerns about how sensitive data is protected. By examining the particular problems associated with protecting sensitive data in the IoT era and guaranteeing the continuous provision of dependable services within smart environments, this research paper seeks to close a significant knowledge gap. In order to do this, the research focuses on the complex data-centric features of smart ecosystems, including data processing, generation, and storage. This paper thoroughly examines the range of current IoT technologies, data management practices, and privacy challenges by using a qualitative research approach. It also offers a thorough examination of the privacy protections and security measures that are now in place in smart buildings and homes. This research focuses primarily on the interface between technology, security, and privacy of data. This work effectively fills in the significant research vacuum by clarifying the specific issues it seeks to solve. It provides useful advice and insights that can help individuals and organizations navigate the complex world of smart technologies, securely store their data, and realize the full potential of these game-changing advancements.},
